anco White’s Flight to Freedom (1815) -- tChapter 11 Unexplored Connections: Spanish Prisoners of War and Political Refugees in France, 1808–1820 -- tEpilogue: The Conquest of History and the Construction of Identitarian Discourses: An Interview with Christopher Schmidt-Nowara -- tList of Works by Christopher Schmidt-Nowara -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years, the historiography of nineteenth-century Spain and Latin America has been invigorated by interdisciplinary engagement with scholars working on topics such as empire, slavery, abolition, race, identity, and captivity. No scholar better exemplified these developments than Christopher Schmidt-Nowara, a specialist on Spain and its Caribbean colonies in Cuba and Puerto Rico. A brilliant career was cut short in 2015 when he died at the age of 48. Rethinking Atlantic Empire takes Schmidt-Nowara’s work as a point of departure, charting scholarly paths that move past reductive national narratives and embrace transnational approaches to the entangled empires of the Atlantic world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aAntislavery movementszLatin AmericaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Spain & Portugal.2bisacsh  aHistory: 18th/19th Century, Colonial History.1 aAlmeida, Joselyn M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEastman, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEastman, Scott, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEller, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoode, Joshua, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobson, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobson, Stephen, e